Due to the spherical symmetry, we only need to consider a cross-section through the center of the sphere. Let \(AB\) be a diameter of the light-emitting disc within this cross-section. Consider a light ray \(B_{1}P_{1}\) emitted from a point \(B_{1}\) on this diameter at a distance \(r\) from the center, which strikes at an incident angle \(\theta_{1}\). Considering \(\triangle P_{1}OB_{1}\), by the law of sines:

\[
\frac{\sin \theta_{1}}{r} = \frac{\sin \varphi_{1}}{R}
\]

Thus:

\[
\sin \theta_{1} = \frac{r}{R} \sin \varphi_{1}
\]

This equation indicates that the incident angle \(\theta_{1}\) reaches its maximum \(\left(\theta_{1}\right)_{\text{max}}\) when \(\varphi_{1} = \frac{\pi}{2}\).

Comparing the maximum incident angles for different luminous points on \(AB\), the light rays emitted perpendicularly to \(AB\) from point \(B\), labeled \(BP\), have the maximum incident angle. Therefore:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\sin \left(\theta_{1}\right)_{\text{max}} & = \frac{r}{R}, \quad r \leqslant \frac{d}{2} \\
\sin \theta_{\max} & = \frac{d/2}{R} = \frac{d}{2R}
\end{aligned}
\]

To prevent total internal reflection, we must have:

\[
\sin \theta_{\max} < \sin \theta_{\mathcal{C}}
\]

Thus:

\[
\begin{gathered}
\frac{d}{2R} < \frac{1}{n} \\
R > \frac{1}{2}nd = 5.1 \, \text{mm}
\end{gathered}
\]

Therefore, the radius of the hemispherical medium must be greater than 5.1 mm to ensure that the light emitted from the disc does not undergo total internal reflection.

The optical path difference $\Delta$ between the focal planes is calculated as follows:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\Delta = -\overline{F_{1}^{\prime}F_{2}} = -8.00 \, \text{cm}.
\end{aligned}
\]

The position of the lens vertex $A$, denoted as $x_{A}$, should satisfy

$$
\begin{gathered}
(n^{2}-1)(x_{A}-x_{0})^{2}=a^{2} \\
x_{A} = x_{0} + \frac{a}{\sqrt{n^{2}-1}} = \frac{\sqrt{f^{2}+R^{2}}+f}{n+1}
\end{gathered}
$$

It is evident that for a given $n$ and $f$, $x_{A}$ is determined by $R$.

As shown in the diagram, a person perceives the glass tube wall thickness as zero when the light rays emerging from the cylindrical glass tube and reaching the eye propagate in a direction tangential to the outer surface of the glass. Due to symmetry, we only need to study a light ray that originates from the liquid and is tangent to the glass tube.

$$
<image 1>
$$

Consider light rays that strike point $A$ on the inner wall from the liquid, forming a light cone with a vertex angle equal to $2 \alpha_{\text{max}}$. After refraction at the glass tube wall, these rays spread out. The rays with a refraction angle $\alpha=\alpha_{\max}$ strike the outer wall point $B$ at an incidence angle $\beta$, emerging along the tube surface in a tangential direction. Therefore, we have the relation

\begin{equation*}
\sin \beta=\frac{1}{n_{1}}
\end{equation*}

Applying the sine rule to triangle $A B O$, we obtain

\[
\frac{r}{\sin \beta}=\frac{R}{\sin \left(180^{\circ}-\alpha\right)}
\]

which simplifies to

\begin{equation*}
\frac{r}{R}=\frac{\sin \beta}{\sin \alpha}
\end{equation*}

It is easy to determine that the given condition can only be satisfied if

\begin{equation*}
\frac{r}{R} \geqslant \frac{1/n_{1}}{\sin \alpha_{\max}}
\end{equation*}

For this scenario, when $n_{2} \leqslant n_{1}$, we have $\sin \alpha_{\max}=\frac{n_{2}}{n_{1}}$, so

\begin{equation*}
\frac{r}{R} \geqslant \frac{1}{n_{2}}
\end{equation*}

As shown in the image, the wall thickness of the glass tube seems to be zero only when the light rays coming out of the cylindrical glass tube and reaching the observer's eye travel along the tangent to the outer surface of the glass. Due to symmetry, we only need to analyze one ray emerging from the liquid that is tangent to the glass tube.
$$
<image 1>
$$

Consider the light ray directed from the liquid towards point $A$ on the inner wall of the tube. Let these rays fall within a light cone with an apex angle of $2 \alpha_{\text{max}}$ and refract at the tube wall spreading out. The ray with a refraction angle $\alpha=\alpha_{\max}$ strikes point $B$ on the outer wall at an incident angle $\beta$, and refracts out along the tangent to the outer surface. Thus, we have the relationship:

\begin{equation*}
\sin \beta=\frac{1}{n_{1}}
\end{equation*}

Applying the sine law to triangle $A B O$, we get:

\[
\frac{r}{\sin \beta}=\frac{R}{\sin \left(180^{\circ}-\alpha\right)}
\]

which simplifies to:

\begin{equation*}
\frac{r}{R}=\frac{\sin \beta}{\sin \alpha}
\end{equation*}

It is easy to determine that this condition is only satisfied when:

\begin{equation*}
\frac{r}{R} \geqslant \frac{1/n_{1}}{\sin \alpha_{\max}}
\end{equation*}

For this scenario, when $n_{2} \geqslant n_{1}$, we have $\alpha_{\text{max}}=90^{\circ}$, and in this case:

\begin{equation*}
\frac{r}{R} \geqslant \frac{1}{n_{1}}
\end{equation*}
